Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Uniform 104-byte node so the walker stays node-kind agnostic. The fields cover
every orthogonal axis a Rust item can carry: name, an auxiliary value slot
(operator text, literal text, or a literal discriminant), an attached type, a
children list, attributes, generics, lifetime params, a where clause, visibility,
mutability, and source position. Leaf nodes leave the unused slots null.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
13 pointer-sized fields, offsets 0-96: 0 node_type, 8 name, 16 value, 24
type_info, 32 children, 40 attributes, 48 generics, 56 lifetime_params, 64
where_clause, 72 visibility, 80 mutability, 88 line, 96 column.
@End Implementation
Type called "RustASTNode":
    node_type as Integer
    name as Integer
    value as Integer
    type_info as Integer
    children as Integer
    attributes as Integer
    generics as Integer
    lifetime_params as Integer
    where_clause as Integer
    visibility as Integer
    mutability as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parser state pairs the streaming lexer with a cached current_token type so the
recursive-descent dispatch reads the token without touching the lexer each time.
The error_message + has_error pair surface parse failures; the cached
current_lexeme is captured eagerly at each advance so a borrowed-pointer is never
read after the lexer recycles it.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
40-byte layout, 5 fields: lexer@0, current_token@8, current_lexeme@16,
error_message@24, has_error@32. current_lexeme holds an owned copy of the current
token's text, refreshed by advance_token, so callers may stash it into AST nodes
safely.
@End Implementation
Type called "RustParser":
    lexer as Integer
    current_token as Integer
    current_lexeme as Integer
    error_message as Integer
    has_error as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation / Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructor couples a fresh lexer with the parser and primes the first token so
the first peek after construction sees a valid token. Failed lexer creation frees
the parser and returns 0.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Allocate 40 bytes; on OOM return 0. Create the lexer over source; on failure
deallocate and return 0. Zero the slots, then advance_token to load token #1.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_rust_parser" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with 40
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lexer be proc create_rust_lexer from Lexer with source
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with parser
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, 0

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases the lexer and the parser struct. AST nodes outlive the parser by design
and are not freed here.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Idempotent on null. Destroys the lexer if present, then deallocates the parser.
@End Implementation
Process called "destroy_rust_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    If lexer is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy_rust_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    End If
    proc deallocate from Layout with parser
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Construction / Setters
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Uniform node factory parameterised by node_type. Pre-zeroes every slot so leaf
nodes need no per-field clearing and setters can detect uninitialised state via
the zero sentinel. Visibility defaults to private (Rust's default).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Allocate 104 bytes; on OOM return 0. Write node_type@0, zero offsets 8..64, write
VIS_PRIVATE@72, zero mutability/line/column.
@End Implementation
Process called "make_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with 104
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, VIS_PRIVATE
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 80, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 88, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 96, 0
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lazily creates the children list on first append so leaves cost no list
allocation. Null guards make it safe from error paths.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Null parent/child returns. Reads children@32; if 0 creates a List and stores it.
Pushes child.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_child" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer:
    If parent is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    If child is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 32
    If children is equal to 0:
        Set children to proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 32, children
    End If
    proc push from List with children, child
End Process

@Reasoning:
Setters for the named slots. name/value copy nothing because the parser already
hands an owned lexeme copy (current_rust_lexeme allocates), so storing the
pointer transfers ownership into the node.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Each null-guards the node then writes the supplied pointer/integer to its slot.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_name" takes node as Integer, name as Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, name
End Process

Process called "set_value" takes node as Integer, value as Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, value
End Process

Process called "set_type_info" takes node as Integer, type_info as Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, type_info
End Process

Process called "set_attributes" takes node as Integer, attributes as Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, attributes
End Process

Process called "set_generics" takes node as Integer, generics as Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, generics
End Process

Process called "set_where_clause" takes node as Integer, where_clause as Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, where_clause
End Process

Process called "set_visibility" takes node as Integer, vis as Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, vis
End Process

Process called "set_mutability" takes node as Integer, is_mut as Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 80, is_mut
End Process

Note: Accessors used by rust_to_hir over the same layout.
Process called "node_type" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
End Process

Process called "node_name" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
End Process

Process called "node_value" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
End Process

Process called "node_type_info" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24
End Process

Process called "node_children" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
End Process

Process called "node_generics" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 48
End Process

Process called "node_visibility" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 72
End Process

Process called "node_mutability" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 80
End Process

@Reasoning:
A node's child count for walkers; the children slot is a List or 0.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read children@32; 0 -> 0; else List.size.
@End Implementation
Process called "node_child_count" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    If children is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc size from List with children
End Process

@Reasoning:
Positional child access for walkers.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read children@32; 0 -> 0; else List.get_at(index).
@End Implementation
Process called "node_child" takes node as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 32
    If children is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get_at from List with children, index
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Advances the lexer one token, caches the new token type, and captures an OWNED
copy of the new token's lexeme immediately. Capturing eagerly (rather than on
demand) avoids the use-after-free class where a borrowed lexeme pointer outlives
the lexer's per-token buffer.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read lexer@0. next_rust_token gives the new type; store at offset 8. Then
current_rust_lexeme allocates an owned copy; store at offset 16.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer:
    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let tt be proc next_rust_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, tt
    Let lx be proc current_rust_lexeme from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, lx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-destructive read of the cached current token type - the primary dispatch
input for every parse_* routine.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns the integer at offset 8.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the OWNED lexeme of the current token (already copied by advance_token),
safe to store in an AST node.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns the pointer at offset 16.
@End Implementation
Process called "current_lexeme" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a parse error: sets the sticky has_error flag and stores a duplicated
message so its lifetime is independent of the caller's literal.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Write 1 to has_error@32; string_duplicate the message into error_message@24.
@End Implementation
Process called "set_error" takes parser as Integer, message as Integer:
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, 1
    Let copy be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, copy
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reads the sticky error flag so the top-level loop can short-circuit.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns the integer at offset 32.
@End Implementation
Process called "has_error" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 32
End Process

@Reasoning:
Asserts the current token is the expected type and consumes it; otherwise records
an error. ALWAYS advances on error too so the enclosing loop cannot spin on the
mismatched token - guaranteeing forward progress (the non-advancing-loop class
bug guard).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read peek. On match advance_token. On mismatch set_error(message) and advance_token
anyway so the cursor moves past the offending token.
@End Implementation
Process called "expect" takes parser as Integer, expected as Integer, message as Integer:
    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is equal to expected:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
        proc set_error with parser, message
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
If the current token matches, consume it and report 1; otherwise leave it and
report 0. Used for optional punctuation (commas, optional keywords).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
peek == tok ? advance_token, return 1 : return 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "accept" takes parser as Integer, tok as Integer returns Integer:
    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is equal to tok:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Program / Item Dispatch
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A Rust crate is a flat list of items. The loop parses items until EOF, attaching
each to the RUST_PROGRAM root. It reads the lexer byte cursor before and after
each item parse and force-advances on zero progress so a malformed item can never
stall the loop (non-advancing-loop guard).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make_node(RUST_PROGRAM). Loop: peek; TOKEN_EOF breaks. Snapshot lexer position;
parse_item; attach if non-null; if the position did not advance AND we are not at
EOF, advance_token to guarantee progress. Returns the program node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_rust_program" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let program be proc make_node with RUST_PROGRAM
    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If

        Let before be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let item be proc parse_item with parser
        If item is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with program, item
        End If

        Let after be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let still be proc peek with parser
        If after is equal to before:
            If still is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return program
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level item dispatch. Optional attributes and visibility precede the item
keyword and are attached to whichever item follows. Leading async/unsafe before
fn are handled inside parse_function. An unrecognised lead is consumed (progress
guard) and yields 0 so the program loop continues.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
parse_attributes, parse_visibility. peek the keyword; dispatch to the matching
parse_*; on a produced node attach attributes and visibility. async/unsafe lead
to parse_function. Unknown -> advance_token, return 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_item" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let attrs be proc parse_attributes with parser
    Let vis be proc parse_visibility with parser
    Let t be proc peek with parser

    Let node be 0

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_FN:
        Set node to proc parse_function with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_ASYNC:
        Set node to proc parse_function with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_UNSAFE:
        Set node to proc parse_function with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STRUCT:
        Set node to proc parse_struct with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_UNION:
        Set node to proc parse_union with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_ENUM:
        Set node to proc parse_enum with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_TRAIT:
        Set node to proc parse_trait with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_IMPL:
        Set node to proc parse_impl with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MOD:
        Set node to proc parse_mod with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_USE:
        Set node to proc parse_use with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_TYPE:
        Set node to proc parse_type_alias with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CONST:
        Set node to proc parse_const with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STATIC:
        Set node to proc parse_static with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EXTERN:
        Set node to proc parse_function with parser
    End If

    If node is not equal to 0:
        proc set_attributes with node, attrs
        proc set_visibility with node, vis
        Return node
    End If

    Note: Unknown lead: ensure progress and skip.
    Let tt be proc peek with parser
    If tt is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Attributes and Visibility
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Collects a run of #[...] attribute tokens into a list of their lexemes. The lexer
emits each whole attribute as one TOKEN_ATTRIBUTE so this loop just gathers them.
Returns 0 (no list) when there are none so callers can cheaply test presence.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
While peek == TOKEN_ATTRIBUTE: lazily create the list, push current_lexeme,
advance. Return the list (or 0).
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_attributes" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let list be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_ATTRIBUTE:
            Break
        End If
        If list is equal to 0:
            Set list to proc create from List
        End If
        Let lx be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc push from List with list, lx
        proc advance_token with parser
    End While
    Return list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses an optional visibility modifier: pub, pub(crate), pub(super), pub(self),
pub(in path). Returns the VIS_* integer. The parenthesised restriction is
consumed but reduced to VIS_PUB_CRATE for the translation pipeline (which emits
`pub` either way; the restriction is not expressible 1:1 in the target IR).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
If peek != TOKEN_PUB return VIS_PRIVATE. Consume pub. If the next token is
TOKEN_LPAREN, consume the balanced parenthesised group and return VIS_PUB_CRATE;
otherwise return VIS_PUB.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_visibility" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PUB:
        Return VIS_PRIVATE
    End If
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let n be proc peek with parser
    If n is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let depth be 1
        While depth is greater than 0:
            Let c be proc peek with parser
            If c is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Break
            End If
            If c is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN:
                Set depth to depth plus 1
            End If
            If c is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN:
                Set depth to depth minus 1
            End If
            proc advance_token with parser
        End While
        Return VIS_PUB_CRATE
    End If
    Return VIS_PUB
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Generics and Where Clauses
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses a generic parameter list <T, U: Bound, 'a, const N: usize>. Each parameter
becomes a RUST_GENERIC_PARAM carrying its name (type param, lifetime, or const
param identifier). Bounds after ':' are consumed up to the next ',' or '>' since
the target IR keeps only the parameter names. Handles nested '<...>' in bounds via
a depth counter so a bound like T: Into<String> does not end the list early.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume '<'. Loop until '>' or EOF: skip leading lifetimes/const keyword, read an
identifier/lifetime name into a RUST_GENERIC_PARAM, then if ':' is present skip
the bound tokens tracking '<'/'>' depth until a top-level ',' or '>'. Consume a
trailing ',' if present. Consume '>'. Returns a RUST_GENERICS node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_generics" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_LT, "Expected '<'"
    Let generics be proc make_node with RUST_GENERICS

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_GT:
            Break
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If

        Note: optional const-generic keyword
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CONST:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        Let pname be proc current_lexeme with parser
        Let param be proc make_node with RUST_GENERIC_PARAM
        proc set_name with param, pname
        Note: consume the param token (identifier or lifetime)
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: optional ': bounds' - skip to top-level ',' or '>'
        Let after be proc peek with parser
        If after is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_COLON:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let depth be 0
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let b be proc peek with parser
                If b is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                    Break
                End If
                If depth is equal to 0:
                    If b is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                        Break
                    End If
                    If b is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_GT:
                        Break
                    End If
                End If
                If b is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
                    Set depth to depth plus 1
                End If
                If b is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_GT:
                    Set depth to depth minus 1
                End If
                proc advance_token with parser
            End While
        End If

        proc add_child with generics, param

        Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        If comma is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_GT, "Expected '>'"
    Return generics
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a where clause `where T: Bound, U: Other`. The target IR keeps the textual
predicates only lightly, so this consumes the predicate tokens up to the item
body (a '{' or ';') tracking generic '<'/'>' depth so an angle-bracketed bound
does not confuse the terminator scan. Returns a RUST_WHERE_CLAUSE node whose
value holds nothing structured (its presence is what callers test).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'where'. Loop: stop at top-level '{' or ';' or EOF; track '<'/'>' depth;
advance otherwise. Returns the where node.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_where_clause" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_WHERE_CLAUSE
    Let depth be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If
        If depth is equal to 0:
            If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
                Break
            End If
            If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
                Break
            End If
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
            Set depth to depth plus 1
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_GT:
            Set depth to depth minus 1
        End If
        proc advance_token with parser
    End While
    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Struct / Union
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses a struct in all three shapes. Generics and an optional where clause precede
the body. A ';' is a unit struct; a '(' begins a tuple struct (positional types
terminated by ');'); a '{' begins a named-field struct.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'struct'; read the name; optional generics; optional where; dispatch on
the next token: ';' unit; '(' parse tuple fields + ');'; '{' parse named fields +
'}'. Returns the RUST_STRUCT node with a RUST_FIELD_LIST child for the fields.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_struct" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_STRUCT

    Let name be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc set_name with node, name
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected struct name"

    Let lt be proc peek with parser
    If lt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
        Let g be proc parse_generics with parser
        proc set_generics with node, g
    End If

    Let wt be proc peek with parser
    If wt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_WHERE:
        Let w be proc parse_where_clause with parser
        proc set_where_clause with node, w
    End If

    Let nt be proc peek with parser
    If nt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If
    If nt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let tf be proc parse_tuple_fields with parser
        proc add_child with node, tf
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')'"
        proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
        Return node
    End If
    If nt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let sf be proc parse_struct_fields with parser
        proc add_child with node, sf
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE, "Expected '}'"
        Return node
    End If

    proc set_error with parser, "Expected ';', '(', or '{' after struct name"
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
A union is structurally identical to a named-field struct for translation; we
parse it as a RUST_UNION with a named-field body.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'union'; name; optional generics; '{' named fields '}'. Returns RUST_UNION.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_union" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_UNION

    Let name be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc set_name with node, name
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected union name"

    Let lt be proc peek with parser
    If lt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
        Let g be proc parse_generics with parser
        proc set_generics with node, g
    End If

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE, "Expected '{'"
    Let sf be proc parse_struct_fields with parser
    proc add_child with node, sf
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE, "Expected '}'"
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses named struct fields `vis name: Type,` into a RUST_FIELD_LIST. Each field
allows its own attributes and visibility. Trailing comma permitted; the loop ends
at '}' or when a field is not followed by a comma.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make RUST_FIELD_LIST. Loop until '}'/EOF: parse_attributes, parse_visibility, read
field name + ':' + parse_type into a RUST_FIELD; attach; if no trailing ',' break.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_struct_fields" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let list be proc make_node with RUST_FIELD_LIST
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE:
            Break
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If

        Let fattrs be proc parse_attributes with parser
        Let fvis be proc parse_visibility with parser

        Let fname be proc current_lexeme with parser
        Let field be proc make_node with RUST_FIELD
        proc set_name with field, fname
        proc set_attributes with field, fattrs
        proc set_visibility with field, fvis
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected field name"
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COLON, "Expected ':'"
        Let ftype be proc parse_type with parser
        proc set_type_info with field, ftype
        proc add_child with list, field

        Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        If comma is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
    End While
    Return list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses positional tuple-struct fields `(T1, T2)` into a RUST_TUPLE_FIELDS list.
Each field is a RUST_FIELD with only a type. Stops at ')'.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make RUST_TUPLE_FIELDS. Loop until ')'/EOF: parse_visibility (positional fields
may be pub), parse_type into a RUST_FIELD; attach; if no ',' break.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_tuple_fields" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let list be proc make_node with RUST_TUPLE_FIELDS
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN:
            Break
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If

        Let fvis be proc parse_visibility with parser
        Let field be proc make_node with RUST_FIELD
        proc set_visibility with field, fvis
        Let ftype be proc parse_type with parser
        proc set_type_info with field, ftype
        proc add_child with list, field

        Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        If comma is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
    End While
    Return list
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Enum
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses an enum with unit, tuple, and struct variants, plus optional explicit
discriminants. Generics and where precede the body.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'enum'; name; optional generics; optional where; '{'; parse variants into
a RUST_VARIANT_LIST; '}'. Returns RUST_ENUM.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_enum" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_ENUM

    Let name be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc set_name with node, name
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected enum name"

    Let lt be proc peek with parser
    If lt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
        Let g be proc parse_generics with parser
        proc set_generics with node, g
    End If

    Let wt be proc peek with parser
    If wt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_WHERE:
        Let w be proc parse_where_clause with parser
        proc set_where_clause with node, w
    End If

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE, "Expected '{'"

    Let variants be proc make_node with RUST_VARIANT_LIST
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE:
            Break
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If

        Let vattrs be proc parse_attributes with parser
        Let vname be proc current_lexeme with parser
        Let variant be proc make_node with RUST_VARIANT
        proc set_name with variant, vname
        proc set_attributes with variant, vattrs
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected variant name"

        Let vt be proc peek with parser
        If vt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let tf be proc parse_tuple_fields with parser
            proc add_child with variant, tf
            proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')'"
            Otherwise:
            If vt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let sf be proc parse_struct_fields with parser
                proc add_child with variant, sf
                proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE, "Expected '}'"
                Otherwise:
                If vt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EQ:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                    Let disc be proc parse_expression with parser
                    proc set_value with variant, disc
                End If
            End If
        End If

        proc add_child with variants, variant

        Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        If comma is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    proc add_child with node, variants
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE, "Expected '}'"
    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Trait / Impl
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses a trait: name, generics, optional supertrait bounds after ':', optional
where, then a brace-delimited list of associated items (methods with or without
bodies, associated types, associated consts). Stored as a RUST_ITEM_LIST child.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'trait'; name; optional generics; if ':' skip supertrait bound tokens to
'{'/where; optional where; '{' parse_assoc_items '}'. Returns RUST_TRAIT.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_trait" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_TRAIT

    Let name be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc set_name with node, name
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected trait name"

    Let lt be proc peek with parser
    If lt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
        Let g be proc parse_generics with parser
        proc set_generics with node, g
    End If

    Note: supertrait bounds
    Let ct be proc peek with parser
    If ct is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_COLON:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let depth be 0
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let b be proc peek with parser
            If b is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Break
            End If
            If depth is equal to 0:
                If b is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
                    Break
                End If
                If b is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_WHERE:
                    Break
                End If
            End If
            If b is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
                Set depth to depth plus 1
            End If
            If b is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_GT:
                Set depth to depth minus 1
            End If
            proc advance_token with parser
        End While
    End If

    Let wt be proc peek with parser
    If wt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_WHERE:
        Let w be proc parse_where_clause with parser
        proc set_where_clause with node, w
    End If

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE, "Expected '{'"
    Let items be proc parse_assoc_items with parser
    proc add_child with node, items
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE, "Expected '}'"
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses an impl block, inherent (`impl T { ... }`) or trait (`impl Trait for T {
... }`). Optional generics directly after `impl` bind the impl. The presence of a
`for` distinguishes a trait impl; the trait reference is stored in the node value
and the target type in type_info.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'impl'; optional generics; parse a type (the trait-or-target). If 'for'
follows, that type was the trait: store it in value, parse the real target type
into type_info. Otherwise store the type in type_info. Optional where; '{'
parse_assoc_items '}'. Returns RUST_IMPL.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_impl" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_IMPL

    Let lt be proc peek with parser
    If lt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
        Let g be proc parse_generics with parser
        proc set_generics with node, g
    End If

    Let first_type be proc parse_type with parser

    Let ft be proc peek with parser
    If ft is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_FOR:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc set_value with node, first_type
        Let target be proc parse_type with parser
        proc set_type_info with node, target
        Otherwise:
        proc set_type_info with node, first_type
    End If

    Let wt be proc peek with parser
    If wt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_WHERE:
        Let w be proc parse_where_clause with parser
        proc set_where_clause with node, w
    End If

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE, "Expected '{'"
    Let items be proc parse_assoc_items with parser
    proc add_child with node, items
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE, "Expected '}'"
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses the associated items inside a trait or impl: functions (with or without
bodies), associated `type` aliases, and associated `const` items. Each is parsed
with its attributes and visibility and added to a RUST_ITEM_LIST. The loop ends at
the closing '}'.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make RUST_ITEM_LIST. Loop until '}'/EOF: parse_attributes, parse_visibility; peek
the keyword; fn/async/unsafe -> parse_function; type -> parse_type_alias; const ->
parse_const; otherwise consume one token (progress guard). Attach attributes and
visibility. Returns the item list.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_assoc_items" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let list be proc make_node with RUST_ITEM_LIST
    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE:
            Break
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If

        Let before be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

        Let attrs be proc parse_attributes with parser
        Let vis be proc parse_visibility with parser
        Let k be proc peek with parser

        Let item be 0
        If k is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_FN:
            Set item to proc parse_function with parser
        End If
        If k is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_ASYNC:
            Set item to proc parse_function with parser
        End If
        If k is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_UNSAFE:
            Set item to proc parse_function with parser
        End If
        If k is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_TYPE:
            Set item to proc parse_type_alias with parser
        End If
        If k is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CONST:
            Set item to proc parse_const with parser
        End If

        If item is not equal to 0:
            proc set_attributes with item, attrs
            proc set_visibility with item, vis
            proc add_child with list, item
            Otherwise:
            Note: progress guard
            Let after be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
            If after is equal to before:
                Let still be proc peek with parser
                If still is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return list
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Function
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses a function with optional async/unsafe/const modifiers and optional extern
ABI prefix, then name, generics, parameter list (including self receivers),
optional `-> ReturnType`, optional where clause, and either a `;` (declaration
only, e.g. a trait method signature) or a block body.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume any leading const/async/unsafe and an `extern "abi"` prefix (mutability
slot records async via 2, unsafe via 1 for downstream emit if needed). Consume
'fn'; name; optional generics; '(' parse params ')'; optional '-> type'; optional
where; ';' or block. Params and body are children; the param list is a
RUST_PARAM_LIST, the body a RUST_BLOCK_EXPR.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_function" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let is_async be 0
    Let is_unsafe be 0
    Let is_const be 0

    Note: leading modifiers in any order
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let m be proc peek with parser
        If m is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_ASYNC:
            Set is_async to 1
            proc advance_token with parser
            Otherwise:
            If m is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_UNSAFE:
                Set is_unsafe to 1
                proc advance_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                If m is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CONST:
                    Set is_const to 1
                    proc advance_token with parser
                    Otherwise:
                    If m is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EXTERN:
                        proc advance_token with parser
                        Note: optional ABI string
                        Let abi be proc peek with parser
                        If abi is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STRING:
                            proc advance_token with parser
                        End If
                        Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_FN, "Expected 'fn'"
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_FUNCTION

    Note: encode async/unsafe in mutability slot: 1=unsafe, 2=async (kept simple)
    If is_async is equal to 1:
        proc set_mutability with node, 2
    End If
    If is_unsafe is equal to 1:
        proc set_mutability with node, 1
    End If

    Let name be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc set_name with node, name
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected function name"

    Let lt be proc peek with parser
    If lt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
        Let g be proc parse_generics with parser
        proc set_generics with node, g
    End If

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN, "Expected '('"
    Let params be proc parse_params with parser
    proc add_child with node, params
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')'"

    Let at be proc peek with parser
    If at is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_ARROW:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let ret be proc parse_type with parser
        proc set_type_info with node, ret
    End If

    Let wt be proc peek with parser
    If wt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_WHERE:
        Let w be proc parse_where_clause with parser
        proc set_where_clause with node, w
    End If

    Let bt be proc peek with parser
    If bt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
        Let body be proc parse_block with parser
        proc add_child with node, body
    End If

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a function parameter list into a RUST_PARAM_LIST. Handles the four receiver
forms (self, &self, &mut self, mut self) and ordinary `pat: Type` params with an
optional leading `mut`. Trailing comma permitted.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make RUST_PARAM_LIST. Loop until ')': parse_param; attach if non-null; if no ','
break.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_params" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let list be proc make_node with RUST_PARAM_LIST
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN:
            Break
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If

        Let param be proc parse_param with parser
        If param is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with list, param
        End If

        Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        If comma is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
    End While
    Return list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses one parameter. Self receivers (self / &self / &mut self / mut self) are
recognised and returned with the name "self" (the borrow/mut detail is not needed
by the target IR which renders &self uniformly). Ordinary params parse a pattern,
expect ':', then a type.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Peek: '&' -> consume, optional lifetime, optional mut, if self consume and return
a self param; otherwise the '&' was a reference type lead, fall through with the
'&' already consumed is avoided by snapshotting - instead we only treat '&self'
specially and rebuild for the general case. 'mut' before self or pattern is
recorded. 'self' alone returns a self param. Else parse_pattern, ':' , parse_type.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_param" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_PARAM
    Let t be proc peek with parser

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SELF:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc set_name with node, "self"
        Return node
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_AMP:
        Note: could be &self / &mut self / &'a self - peek beyond
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let n be proc peek with parser
        If n is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LIFETIME:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set n to proc peek with parser
        End If
        Let was_mut be 0
        If n is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MUT:
            Set was_mut to 1
            proc advance_token with parser
            Set n to proc peek with parser
        End If
        If n is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SELF:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc set_name with node, "self"
            proc set_mutability with node, was_mut
            Return node
        End If
        Note: Not a self receiver: the '&' began a referenced pattern is rare;
        Note: treat the remaining as a plain pattern/type param.
        Let pat0 be proc parse_pattern with parser
        proc add_child with node, pat0
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COLON, "Expected ':'"
        Let ty0 be proc parse_type with parser
        proc set_type_info with node, ty0
        Return node
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MUT:
        Note: consume `mut`; the now-current token decides `mut self` vs `mut pat`.
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let after_mut be proc peek with parser
        If after_mut is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SELF:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc set_name with node, "self"
            proc set_mutability with node, 1
            Return node
        End If
        proc set_mutability with node, 1
    End If

    Let pat be proc parse_pattern with parser
    proc add_child with node, pat
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COLON, "Expected ':'"
    Let ty be proc parse_type with parser
    proc set_type_info with node, ty
    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Module / Use / Type Alias / Const / Static
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses a module: `mod name;` (external file, no body) or `mod name { items }`. The
inline body recursively parses items into the module node's children.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'mod'; name; if ';' return (declaration); if '{' loop parse_item until '}'
attaching children. Returns RUST_MODULE.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_mod" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_MODULE

    Let name be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc set_name with node, name
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected module name"

    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE, "Expected '{'"
    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let it be proc peek with parser
        If it is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE:
            Break
        End If
        If it is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If
        Let before be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let item be proc parse_item with parser
        If item is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with node, item
        End If
        Let after be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        If after is equal to before:
            Let still be proc peek with parser
            If still is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If
        End If
    End While
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE, "Expected '}'"
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a use declaration including simple paths, `as` aliases, glob `*`, and
nested `{a, b::c}` groups. The full path text is reconstructed into the node name
so the backend can emit `use path::...;`. Nested groups and globs are captured in
the name with their delimiters preserved.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'use'. Build a name string by walking path segments separated by '::',
appending '*' for glob, ' as alias' for renames, and bracketed groups for nested
imports, until ';'. Consume ';'. Returns RUST_USE with the reconstructed path as
its name.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_use" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_USE

    Let path be proc build_use_path with parser
    proc set_name with node, path
    proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reconstructs a use-tree's textual path. Walks tokens until the terminating ';',
concatenating identifiers, '::' separators, '*' globs, ' as ' aliases, and
'{...}' nested groups verbatim. The reconstruction lets the backend emit a valid
`use` line without modelling the tree structurally.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Start with an empty string. Loop until ';'/EOF: on identifier/self/super/crate
append the lexeme; on TOKEN_SCOPE append "::"; on TOKEN_STAR append "*"; on
TOKEN_AS append " as "; on '{' append "{" and recurse the group bytes; on '}'
append "}"; on ',' append ", ". advance each. Returns the built string.
@End Implementation
Process called "build_use_path" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let acc be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with ""
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
            Break
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If

        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SCOPE:
            Set acc to proc str_append with acc, "::"
            Otherwise:
            If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STAR:
                Set acc to proc str_append with acc, "*"
                Otherwise:
                If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_AS:
                    Set acc to proc str_append with acc, " as "
                    Otherwise:
                    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
                        Set acc to proc str_append with acc, "{"
                        Otherwise:
                        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE:
                            Set acc to proc str_append with acc, "}"
                            Otherwise:
                            If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA:
                                Set acc to proc str_append with acc, ", "
                                Otherwise:
                                Let lx be proc current_lexeme with parser
                                Set acc to proc str_append with acc, lx
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        proc advance_token with parser
    End While
    Return acc
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a type alias `type Name<...> = Type;` (free or associated). Associated
trait `type Name;` (no '=') is permitted.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'type'; name; optional generics; if '=' parse the aliased type into
type_info; ';'. Returns RUST_TYPE_ALIAS.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_type_alias" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_TYPE_ALIAS

    Let name be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc set_name with node, name
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected type name"

    Let lt be proc peek with parser
    If lt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
        Let g be proc parse_generics with parser
        proc set_generics with node, g
    End If

    Let et be proc peek with parser
    If et is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EQ:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let ty be proc parse_type with parser
        proc set_type_info with node, ty
    End If

    proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a const item `const NAME: Type = expr;` (or associated `const NAME: Type;`
in a trait). The type goes to type_info, the initialiser to a child.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'const'; name; ':' type; if '=' parse initialiser as child; ';'. Returns
RUST_CONST.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_const" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_CONST

    Let name be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc set_name with node, name
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected const name"
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COLON, "Expected ':'"
    Let ty be proc parse_type with parser
    proc set_type_info with node, ty

    Let et be proc peek with parser
    If et is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EQ:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let init be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with node, init
    End If

    proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a static item `static [mut] NAME: Type = expr;`. Mutability is recorded.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'static'; optional 'mut'; name; ':' type; '=' initialiser child; ';'.
Returns RUST_STATIC.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_static" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_STATIC

    Let mt be proc peek with parser
    If mt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MUT:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc set_mutability with node, 1
    End If

    Let name be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc set_name with node, name
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, "Expected static name"
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COLON, "Expected ':'"
    Let ty be proc parse_type with parser
    proc set_type_info with node, ty

    Let et be proc peek with parser
    If et is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EQ:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let init be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with node, init
    End If

    proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Types
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Type dispatch off the first token: '&' reference, '*' raw pointer, '[' array or
slice, '(' tuple or unit, 'fn' function type, 'dyn' trait object, 'impl' impl
Trait, 'Self' / identifier path type. Path types carry generic arguments.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read peek; dispatch to the specialised type parser; default to a path type.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let t be proc peek with parser

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_AMP:
        Return proc parse_reference_type with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STAR:
        Return proc parse_pointer_type with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Return proc parse_array_or_slice_type with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN:
        Return proc parse_tuple_type with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_DYN:
        Return proc parse_dyn_type with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_IMPL:
        Return proc parse_impl_trait_type with parser
    End If
    Return proc parse_path_type with parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reference type &T, &mut T, &'a T, &'a mut T. Lifetime and mutability are consumed;
mutability is recorded so the backend can emit &mut.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume '&'; optional lifetime; optional 'mut' (set mutability); parse inner type
as child. Returns RUST_REFERENCE_TYPE.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_reference_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_REFERENCE_TYPE

    Let lt be proc peek with parser
    If lt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LIFETIME:
        Let lf be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc set_name with node, lf
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Let mt be proc peek with parser
    If mt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MUT:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc set_mutability with node, 1
    End If

    Let inner be proc parse_type with parser
    proc add_child with node, inner
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Raw pointer type *const T / *mut T. Mutability recorded.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume '*'; consume 'const' or 'mut' (mut sets mutability); inner type child.
Returns RUST_POINTER_TYPE.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_pointer_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_POINTER_TYPE

    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MUT:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc set_mutability with node, 1
        Otherwise:
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CONST:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If
    End If

    Let inner be proc parse_type with parser
    proc add_child with node, inner
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Array `[T; N]` or slice `[T]`. The presence of `;` after the element type
distinguishes them; the size expression is captured for arrays.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume '['; parse element type as child; if ';' parse the size expr as a second
child and produce RUST_ARRAY_TYPE; else RUST_SLICE_TYPE. Consume ']'.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_array_or_slice_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let elem be proc parse_type with parser

    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let node be proc make_node with RUST_ARRAY_TYPE
        proc add_child with node, elem
        Let size be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with node, size
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET, "Expected ']'"
        Return node
    End If

    Let snode be proc make_node with RUST_SLICE_TYPE
    proc add_child with snode, elem
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET, "Expected ']'"
    Return snode
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tuple type `(T, U)`, unit `()`, or a parenthesised single type. A trailing comma
or more than one element makes it a tuple; `()` is the unit type.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume '('. If immediately ')' return RUST_UNIT_TYPE. Otherwise parse types
separated by ','; if exactly one and no trailing comma, return that inner type
directly; else RUST_TUPLE_TYPE with the element types as children. Consume ')'.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_tuple_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return proc make_node with RUST_UNIT_TYPE
    End If

    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_TUPLE_TYPE
    Let count be 0
    Let trailing be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let pt be proc peek with parser
        If pt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN:
            Break
        End If
        If pt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If
        Let elem be proc parse_type with parser
        proc add_child with node, elem
        Set count to count plus 1
        Set trailing to 0
        Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        If comma is equal to 1:
            Set trailing to 1
            Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')'"

    If count is equal to 1:
        If trailing is equal to 0:
            Return proc node_child with node, 0
        End If
    End If
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
dyn Trait object type `dyn Trait + 'a`. The trait path is parsed as the inner
type; additional `+ bound` parts are consumed.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'dyn'; parse a path type child; consume any `+ ...` bound continuations.
Returns RUST_DYN_TRAIT_TYPE.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_dyn_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_DYN_TRAIT_TYPE
    Let inner be proc parse_path_type with parser
    proc add_child with node, inner
    proc consume_type_bound_plus with parser
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
impl Trait type (in argument/return position) `impl Trait + Send`. Modelled like
dyn for translation purposes.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'impl'; parse a path type child; consume `+ ...` continuations. Returns
RUST_IMPL_TRAIT_TYPE.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_impl_trait_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_IMPL_TRAIT_TYPE
    Let inner be proc parse_path_type with parser
    proc add_child with node, inner
    proc consume_type_bound_plus with parser
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes trailing `+ Bound` continuations in dyn/impl Trait types and lifetime
bounds, tracking generic depth so `+ Into<X>` is consumed whole.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
While peek == '+': consume it, then consume one path type (or lifetime). Stops at
the first non-'+'.
@End Implementation
Process called "consume_type_bound_plus" takes parser as Integer:
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PLUS:
            Break
        End If
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let n be proc peek with parser
        If n is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LIFETIME:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Otherwise:
            Let discard be proc parse_path_type with parser
        End If
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Path type Foo, std::vec::Vec<T>, Self, Option<T>. Segments separated by '::' are
joined into the node name; the final segment's generic arguments `<...>` become
child type nodes so the backend can emit `Name<Arg, ...>`.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make RUST_PATH_TYPE. Build the name by reading the first segment lexeme (ident /
Self / crate / super / self) then, while '::' follows, append "::" + the next
segment. After the last segment, if '<' parse generic args as children. Returns
the path type.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_path_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_PATH_TYPE
    Let name be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc set_name with node, name
    proc advance_token with parser

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SCOPE:
            Break
        End If
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let seg be proc current_lexeme with parser
        Let combined be proc str_append with name, "::"
        Set combined to proc str_append with combined, seg
        Set name to combined
        proc set_name with node, name
        proc advance_token with parser
    End While

    Let lt be proc peek with parser
    If lt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
        proc advance_token with parser
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let a be proc peek with parser
            If a is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_GT:
                Break
            End If
            If a is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Break
            End If
            If a is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LIFETIME:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                Let arg be proc parse_type with parser
                proc add_child with node, arg
            End If
            Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
            If comma is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
        End While
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_GT, "Expected '>'"
    End If

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Patterns
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Pattern dispatch: '_' wildcard, '&' reference pattern, 'mut'/'ref' binding, '('
tuple, '[' slice, identifier (binding, path constructor, struct, or enum ctor), a
literal otherwise. Or-patterns `a | b` and `@` bindings are handled at the top.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
parse_pattern_primary for the base, then if '|' follows wrap subsequent
alternatives in a RUST_PATTERN_OR; if '@' follows wrap in a RUST_PATTERN_BINDING.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_pattern" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let first be proc parse_pattern_primary with parser

    Let at be proc peek with parser
    If at is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_AT:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let bound be proc parse_pattern_primary with parser
        Let bind be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_BINDING
        proc add_child with bind, first
        proc add_child with bind, bound
        Set first to bind
    End If

    Let pt be proc peek with parser
    If pt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PIPE:
        Let ornode be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_OR
        proc add_child with ornode, first
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let p be proc peek with parser
            If p is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PIPE:
                Break
            End If
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let alt be proc parse_pattern_primary with parser
            proc add_child with ornode, alt
        End While
        Return ornode
    End If

    Return first
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a single (non-or) pattern. Handles wildcard, reference, mut/ref bindings,
tuple, slice, identifier-led forms (plain binding, path::Variant, tuple-ctor
Variant(..), struct-ctor Path { .. }), rest `..`, and literal patterns including
ranges.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Big dispatch on peek. For identifiers, after reading the path, inspect the
follow token: '(' -> enum/tuple ctor pattern; '{' -> struct pattern; '::' already
consumed in the path; else a plain binding. Literals (int/float/string/char/bool)
may form a range with '..='/'..'.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_pattern_primary" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let t be proc peek with parser

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Note: '_' arrives as an identifier whose lexeme is "_"
        Let lx be proc current_lexeme with parser
        Let is_wild be proc string_equals from StringCore with lx, "_"
        If is_wild is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_WILDCARD
        End If
        Return proc parse_pattern_path with parser
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SELF_TYPE:
        Return proc parse_pattern_path with parser
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_AMP:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let mt be proc peek with parser
        If mt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MUT:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If
        Let node be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_REF
        Let inner be proc parse_pattern_primary with parser
        proc add_child with node, inner
        Return node
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_REF:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let mt2 be proc peek with parser
        If mt2 is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MUT:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If
        Let lx2 be proc current_lexeme with parser
        Let node2 be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_IDENT
        proc set_name with node2, lx2
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node2
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MUT:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let lx3 be proc current_lexeme with parser
        Let node3 be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_IDENT
        proc set_name with node3, lx3
        proc set_mutability with node3, 1
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node3
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let tup be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_TUPLE
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let pt be proc peek with parser
            If pt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN:
                Break
            End If
            If pt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Break
            End If
            Let elem be proc parse_pattern with parser
            proc add_child with tup, elem
            Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
            If comma is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
        End While
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')'"
        Return tup
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let arr be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_TUPLE
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let pt2 be proc peek with parser
            If pt2 is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET:
                Break
            End If
            If pt2 is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Break
            End If
            Let elem2 be proc parse_pattern with parser
            proc add_child with arr, elem2
            Let comma2 be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
            If comma2 is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
        End While
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET, "Expected ']'"
        Return arr
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_DOTDOT:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_REST
    End If

    Note: literal pattern (with possible range)
    Return proc parse_pattern_literal with parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses an identifier-led pattern path and refines it: plain binding `x`, qualified
`Mod::Variant`, tuple-ctor `Variant(p, ..)`, or struct-ctor `Path { f: p, .. }`.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Build the path name across '::' segments. Then on '(' -> RUST_PATTERN_ENUM with
sub-patterns; on '{' -> RUST_PATTERN_STRUCT with field sub-patterns; otherwise a
RUST_PATTERN_IDENT binding named by the (single-segment) path.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_pattern_path" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let name be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc advance_token with parser
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let s be proc peek with parser
        If s is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SCOPE:
            Break
        End If
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let seg be proc current_lexeme with parser
        Let combined be proc str_append with name, "::"
        Set combined to proc str_append with combined, seg
        Set name to combined
        proc advance_token with parser
    End While

    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let node be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_ENUM
        proc set_name with node, name
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let pt be proc peek with parser
            If pt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN:
                Break
            End If
            If pt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Break
            End If
            Let sub be proc parse_pattern with parser
            proc add_child with node, sub
            Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
            If comma is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
        End While
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')'"
        Return node
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let snode be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_STRUCT
        proc set_name with snode, name
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let pt2 be proc peek with parser
            If pt2 is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE:
                Break
            End If
            If pt2 is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Break
            End If
            If pt2 is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_DOTDOT:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let rest be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_REST
                proc add_child with snode, rest
                Otherwise:
                Let fname be proc current_lexeme with parser
                Let fld be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_FIELD
                proc set_name with fld, fname
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let colon be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COLON
                If colon is equal to 1:
                    Let fpat be proc parse_pattern with parser
                    proc add_child with fld, fpat
                End If
                proc add_child with snode, fld
            End If
            Let comma2 be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
            If comma2 is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
        End While
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE, "Expected '}'"
        Return snode
    End If

    Let node3 be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_IDENT
    proc set_name with node3, name
    Return node3
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a literal pattern and an optional range `lo..=hi` / `lo..hi`. Booleans and
the unsigned/signed literals are all captured by lexeme; the range form pairs two
literal endpoints.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read a literal node via parse_literal_node. If '..='/'..' follows, parse the
second endpoint and produce a RUST_PATTERN_RANGE with both children. Otherwise wrap
the single literal as a RUST_PATTERN_LITERAL.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_pattern_literal" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lo be proc parse_literal_node with parser
    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_DOTDOTEQ:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let hi be proc parse_literal_node with parser
        Let r be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_RANGE
        proc add_child with r, lo
        proc add_child with r, hi
        Return r
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_DOTDOT:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let hi2 be proc parse_literal_node with parser
        Let r2 be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_RANGE
        proc add_child with r2, lo
        proc add_child with r2, hi2
        Return r2
    End If

    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_PATTERN_LITERAL
    proc add_child with node, lo
    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Block and Statements
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Parses a brace-delimited block `{ stmts... tail? }` into a RUST_BLOCK_EXPR. Each
statement is parsed by parse_statement; a final expression without a trailing
semicolon becomes the block's tail (kept as the last child). The loop reads the
lexer cursor to guarantee progress.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume '{'. Loop until '}'/EOF: snapshot position; parse_statement; attach; if the
cursor did not move, force-advance. Consume '}'. Returns RUST_BLOCK_EXPR.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_block" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE, "Expected '{'"
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_BLOCK_EXPR
    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE:
            Break
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If

        Let before be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Let stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
        If stmt is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with node, stmt
        End If
        Let after be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        If after is equal to before:
            Let still be proc peek with parser
            If still is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE, "Expected '}'"
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses one statement: a `let` binding (incl let-else and type annotation), an
item statement (nested fn/struct/etc.), or an expression statement. A trailing
';' after an expression marks it as a statement (value discarded); without ';' the
expression is the block tail.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
peek: 'let' -> parse_let; an item keyword -> parse_item wrapped as RUST_ITEM_STMT;
else parse_expression, then accept an optional ';' producing RUST_EXPR_STMT (the
';' presence is recorded in mutability: 1 = had semicolon).
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let t be proc peek with parser

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LET:
        Return proc parse_let with parser
    End If

    Let is_item be proc is_item_keyword with t
    If is_item is equal to 1:
        Let item be proc parse_item with parser
        Let wrap be proc make_node with RUST_ITEM_STMT
        proc add_child with wrap, item
        Return wrap
    End If

    Let expr be proc parse_expression with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_EXPR_STMT
    proc add_child with node, expr
    Let semi be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    proc set_mutability with node, semi
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Classifies a token as introducing a nested item inside a block (fn, struct, enum,
trait, impl, mod, use, type, const, static, union). Used to route item statements.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns 1 for any of the item-introducing keyword tokens, else 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_item_keyword" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_FN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STRUCT:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_ENUM:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_TRAIT:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_IMPL:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MOD:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_USE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_UNION:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a let binding: `let pat: Type = expr;` with optional type and initialiser,
and the let-else form `let pat = expr else { block };`. The pattern is the node
name target (stored as a child pattern), the type in type_info, the initialiser as
a child, and an else-block (if present) as a further child.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'let'; parse_pattern as child 0; if ':' parse_type into type_info; if '='
parse the initialiser as child 1; if 'else' parse the diverging block as child 2;
';'. Returns RUST_LET_STMT.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_let" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_LET_STMT

    Let pat be proc parse_pattern with parser
    proc add_child with node, pat

    Let ct be proc peek with parser
    If ct is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_COLON:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let ty be proc parse_type with parser
        proc set_type_info with node, ty
    End If

    Let et be proc peek with parser
    If et is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EQ:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let init be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with node, init

        Let elt be proc peek with parser
        If elt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_ELSE:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let elseblk be proc parse_block with parser
            proc add_child with node, elseblk
        End If
    End If

    proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expressions (precedence climbing)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level expression entry. Assignment is the lowest-precedence, right-associative
operator and must be handled here so that `parse_expression` consumes `=` (a
non-advancing-loop hazard if omitted). Assignment and compound-assignment are
recognised after parsing the LHS; otherwise the parsed value is returned.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse a range-level expression (which descends through the binary precedence
ladder). If the next token is '=' or a compound assign, build a RUST_ASSIGNMENT
whose value holds the operator lexeme, with LHS and RHS (parse_expression
recursively for right-associativity) as children.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lhs be proc parse_range_expr with parser

    Let t be proc peek with parser
    Let is_assign be proc is_assign_op with t
    If is_assign is equal to 1:
        Let op be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let rhs be proc parse_expression with parser
        Let node be proc make_node with RUST_ASSIGNMENT
        proc set_value with node, op
        proc add_child with node, lhs
        proc add_child with node, rhs
        Return node
    End If

    Return lhs
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recognises plain '=' and the compound assignment operators.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns 1 for =, +=, -=, *=, /=, %=, &=, |=, ^=, <<=, >>=; else 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_assign_op" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EQ:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PLUSEQ:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MINUSEQ:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STAREQ:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SLASHEQ:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PERCENTEQ:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_AMPEQ:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PIPEEQ:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CARETEQ:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SHLEQ:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SHREQ:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Range expressions `a..b`, `a..=b`, and prefix/half-open forms. Ranges sit just
above assignment in Rust precedence. The operands are parsed at the logical-or
level below.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse a logical-or expression as the start. If '..' or '..=' follows, parse an
optional end operand (absent for `a..`) and build a RUST_RANGE with the inclusive
flag recorded in mutability (1 = inclusive). Returns the range or the start.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_range_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let start be proc parse_or_expr with parser

    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_DOTDOT:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let node be proc make_node with RUST_RANGE
        proc add_child with node, start
        Let nt be proc peek with parser
        Let has_end be proc starts_expression with nt
        If has_end is equal to 1:
            Let endv be proc parse_or_expr with parser
            proc add_child with node, endv
        End If
        Return node
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_DOTDOTEQ:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let node2 be proc make_node with RUST_RANGE
        proc set_mutability with node2, 1
        proc add_child with node2, start
        Let endv2 be proc parse_or_expr with parser
        proc add_child with node2, endv2
        Return node2
    End If

    Return start
End Process

@Reasoning:
Heuristic for whether the current token can begin an expression, used to decide if
a range has an end operand. Covers literals, identifiers, prefix operators, and
opening brackets.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns 1 for identifier/self/literal/'('/'['/'-'/'!'/'&'/'*'/'|'/move and the
control-flow expression keywords; else 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "starts_expression" takes t as Integer returns Integer:
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SELF:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SELF_TYPE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_INTEGER:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_FLOAT:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STRING:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CHAR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_TRUE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_FALSE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MINUS:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_BANG:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_AMP:
        Return 1
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STAR:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Logical OR `||` - lowest binary precedence above ranges. Left-associative.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse a logical-and operand; while '||' follows, fold into a left-leaning
RUST_BINARY_OP whose value is the operator lexeme.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_or_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_and_expr with parser
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PIPEPIPE:
            Break
        End If
        Let op be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let right be proc parse_and_expr with parser
        Set left to proc make_binary with op, left, right
    End While
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Logical AND `&&`. Left-associative, above OR.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse a comparison operand; fold '&&' chains left.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_and_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_cmp_expr with parser
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_AMPAMP:
            Break
        End If
        Let op be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let right be proc parse_cmp_expr with parser
        Set left to proc make_binary with op, left, right
    End While
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Comparison operators == != < > <= >=. Non-associative in Rust but parsed
left-associatively (rustc rejects chains; we preserve structure faithfully).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse a bit-or operand; fold any comparison operator.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_cmp_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_bitor_expr with parser
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        Let is_cmp be 0
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EQEQ:
            Set is_cmp to 1
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_NE:
            Set is_cmp to 1
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
            Set is_cmp to 1
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_GT:
            Set is_cmp to 1
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LE:
            Set is_cmp to 1
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_GE:
            Set is_cmp to 1
        End If
        If is_cmp is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let op be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let right be proc parse_bitor_expr with parser
        Set left to proc make_binary with op, left, right
    End While
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bitwise OR `|`. Above comparison.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse a bit-xor operand; fold '|' chains.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_bitor_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_bitxor_expr with parser
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PIPE:
            Break
        End If
        Let op be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let right be proc parse_bitxor_expr with parser
        Set left to proc make_binary with op, left, right
    End While
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bitwise XOR `^`. Above bit-or.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse a bit-and operand; fold '^' chains.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_bitxor_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_bitand_expr with parser
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CARET:
            Break
        End If
        Let op be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let right be proc parse_bitand_expr with parser
        Set left to proc make_binary with op, left, right
    End While
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bitwise AND `&`. Above bit-xor.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse a shift operand; fold '&' chains.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_bitand_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_shift_expr with parser
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_AMP:
            Break
        End If
        Let op be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let right be proc parse_shift_expr with parser
        Set left to proc make_binary with op, left, right
    End While
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Shift operators << >>. Above bit-and (matching Rust: shift binds tighter than
the bitwise ops).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse an additive operand; fold << / >> chains.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_shift_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_add_expr with parser
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        Let is_sh be 0
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SHL:
            Set is_sh to 1
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SHR:
            Set is_sh to 1
        End If
        If is_sh is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let op be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let right be proc parse_add_expr with parser
        Set left to proc make_binary with op, left, right
    End While
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Additive operators + and -. Above shift.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse a multiplicative operand; fold +/- chains.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_add_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_mul_expr with parser
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        Let is_add be 0
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PLUS:
            Set is_add to 1
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MINUS:
            Set is_add to 1
        End If
        If is_add is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let op be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let right be proc parse_mul_expr with parser
        Set left to proc make_binary with op, left, right
    End While
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multiplicative operators * / %. Above additive, below cast.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse a cast operand; fold * / % chains.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_mul_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be proc parse_cast_expr with parser
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        Let is_mul be 0
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STAR:
            Set is_mul to 1
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SLASH:
            Set is_mul to 1
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PERCENT:
            Set is_mul to 1
        End If
        If is_mul is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let op be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let right be proc parse_cast_expr with parser
        Set left to proc make_binary with op, left, right
    End While
    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cast `expr as Type`. Above multiplicative, below unary. Multiple casts chain
left-associatively.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse a unary operand; while 'as' follows, parse a type and wrap in a RUST_CAST
with the value as child 0 and the target type in type_info.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_cast_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let value be proc parse_unary_expr with parser
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_AS:
            Break
        End If
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let ty be proc parse_type with parser
        Let node be proc make_node with RUST_CAST
        proc add_child with node, value
        proc set_type_info with node, ty
        Set value to node
    End While
    Return value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Prefix unary operators: negation `-`, logical/bitwise not `!`, dereference `*`,
and reference `&` / `&mut`. These bind tighter than binary operators and looser
than postfix. Reference and deref are distinct node kinds for the backend.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
peek: '-' or '!' -> RUST_UNARY_OP with the operator lexeme and the recursively
parsed operand; '*' -> RUST_DEREFERENCE; '&' (optional 'mut') -> RUST_BORROW with
mutability recorded. Otherwise descend to postfix.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_unary_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let t be proc peek with parser

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MINUS:
        Let op be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let operand be proc parse_unary_expr with parser
        Let node be proc make_node with RUST_UNARY_OP
        proc set_value with node, op
        proc add_child with node, operand
        Return node
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_BANG:
        Let op2 be proc current_lexeme with parser
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let operand2 be proc parse_unary_expr with parser
        Let node2 be proc make_node with RUST_UNARY_OP
        proc set_value with node2, op2
        proc add_child with node2, operand2
        Return node2
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STAR:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let operand3 be proc parse_unary_expr with parser
        Let node3 be proc make_node with RUST_DEREFERENCE
        proc add_child with node3, operand3
        Return node3
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_AMP:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let node4 be proc make_node with RUST_BORROW
        Let mt be proc peek with parser
        If mt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MUT:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc set_mutability with node4, 1
        End If
        Let operand4 be proc parse_unary_expr with parser
        proc add_child with node4, operand4
        Return node4
    End If

    Return proc parse_postfix_expr with parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Postfix chain over a primary: method calls `.name(args)`, field access `.name`,
tuple index `.0`, function call `(args)`, indexing `[expr]`, the `?` try operator,
and `.await`. Left-associative; each postfix wraps the prior result.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Parse a primary. Loop: '.' -> read the member; if it is 'await' make RUST_AWAIT;
elif '(' follows make RUST_METHOD_CALL (receiver + args); else RUST_FIELD_ACCESS
(member in node value). '(' -> RUST_FUNCTION_CALL with callee + args. '[' ->
RUST_ARRAY_ACCESS with collection + index. '?' -> RUST_TRY. Any other token ends
the chain.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_postfix_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let expr be proc parse_primary_expr with parser

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser

        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_DOT:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let mt be proc peek with parser
            If mt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_AWAIT:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let aw be proc make_node with RUST_AWAIT
                proc add_child with aw, expr
                Set expr to aw
                Otherwise:
                Let member be proc current_lexeme with parser
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let after be proc peek with parser
                If after is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN:
                    Note: method call
                    proc advance_token with parser
                    Let call be proc make_node with RUST_METHOD_CALL
                    proc set_name with call, member
                    proc add_child with call, expr
                    proc parse_call_args with parser, call
                    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')'"
                    Set expr to call
                    Otherwise:
                    Let fa be proc make_node with RUST_FIELD_ACCESS
                    proc set_name with fa, member
                    proc add_child with fa, expr
                    Set expr to fa
                End If
            End If
            Otherwise:
            If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let fcall be proc make_node with RUST_FUNCTION_CALL
                proc add_child with fcall, expr
                proc parse_call_args with parser, fcall
                proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')'"
                Set expr to fcall
                Otherwise:
                If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                    Let idx be proc make_node with RUST_ARRAY_ACCESS
                    proc add_child with idx, expr
                    Let index be proc parse_expression with parser
                    proc add_child with idx, index
                    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET, "Expected ']'"
                    Set expr to idx
                    Otherwise:
                    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_QUESTION:
                        proc advance_token with parser
                        Let tr be proc make_node with RUST_TRY
                        proc add_child with tr, expr
                        Set expr to tr
                        Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return expr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a comma-separated argument list into the given call node (each argument is
an expression child). Trailing comma permitted. Stops at ')'.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Loop until ')'/EOF: parse_expression, attach; if no ',' break.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_call_args" takes parser as Integer, call as Integer:
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN:
            Return
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Return
        End If
        Let arg be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with call, arg
        Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        If comma is equal to 0:
            Return
        End If
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Primary expressions: literals, parenthesised/tuple/unit, array literals, block
expressions, control-flow expressions (if/if-let, match, loop, while/while-let,
for), closures (incl move), return/break/continue, and identifier/path-led forms
which may continue into a macro call `name!(...)` or a struct literal `Path { .. }`.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Dispatch on peek. Literals build a RUST_LITERAL via parse_literal_node-derived
node. '(' -> parse_paren_or_tuple. '[' -> parse_array_expr. '{' -> parse_block.
Keyword leads -> the matching control-flow parser. '|' or move -> closure. ident/
self/Self/crate/super -> parse_path_expr (which handles macro and struct-literal
continuations).
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_primary_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let t be proc peek with parser

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_INTEGER:
        Return proc parse_literal_node with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_FLOAT:
        Return proc parse_literal_node with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STRING:
        Return proc parse_literal_node with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_BYTE_STRING:
        Return proc parse_literal_node with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CHAR:
        Return proc parse_literal_node with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_TRUE:
        Return proc parse_literal_node with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_FALSE:
        Return proc parse_literal_node with parser
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN:
        Return proc parse_paren_or_tuple with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Return proc parse_array_expr with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
        Return proc parse_block with parser
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_IF:
        Return proc parse_if_expr with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MATCH:
        Return proc parse_match_expr with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LOOP:
        Return proc parse_loop_expr with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_WHILE:
        Return proc parse_while_expr with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_FOR:
        Return proc parse_for_expr with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_UNSAFE:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return proc parse_block with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_ASYNC:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let mv be proc peek with parser
        If mv is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MOVE:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If
        Return proc parse_block with parser
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MOVE:
        Return proc parse_closure with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PIPE:
        Return proc parse_closure with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PIPEPIPE:
        Return proc parse_closure with parser
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RETURN:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let node be proc make_node with RUST_RETURN
        Let nt be proc peek with parser
        Let has be proc starts_expression with nt
        If has is equal to 1:
            Let v be proc parse_expression with parser
            proc add_child with node, v
        End If
        Return node
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_BREAK:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let bnode be proc make_node with RUST_BREAK
        Let bt be proc peek with parser
        Let bhas be proc starts_expression with bt
        If bhas is equal to 1:
            Let bv be proc parse_expression with parser
            proc add_child with bnode, bv
        End If
        Return bnode
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CONTINUE:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return proc make_node with RUST_CONTINUE
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Return proc parse_path_expr with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SELF:
        Return proc parse_path_expr with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SELF_TYPE:
        Return proc parse_path_expr with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CRATE:
        Return proc parse_path_expr with parser
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SUPER:
        Return proc parse_path_expr with parser
    End If

    Note: Unknown lead in expression position - recover by capturing the current
    Note: token's lexeme as an identifier node and advancing, so the enclosing
    Note: expression loops always make forward progress (non-advancing-loop guard).
    Let recovery be proc make_node with RUST_IDENTIFIER
    Let lx be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc set_name with recovery, lx
    Let et be proc peek with parser
    If et is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If
    Return recovery
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds a literal node, recording the value text and a literal-kind discriminant in
the node value_type-equivalent slot (stored in mutability here since the AST node
has no separate value_type field; rust_to_hir reads it). Booleans store "true"/
"false".
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read the token type and lexeme; make RUST_LITERAL; set value=lexeme; set the kind
discriminant in mutability (RUST_LIT_INTEGER/FLOAT/STRING/CHAR/BOOL). advance.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_literal_node" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let t be proc peek with parser
    Let lx be proc current_lexeme with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_LITERAL
    proc set_value with node, lx

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_INTEGER:
        proc set_mutability with node, RUST_LIT_INTEGER
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_FLOAT:
        proc set_mutability with node, RUST_LIT_FLOAT
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_STRING:
        proc set_mutability with node, RUST_LIT_STRING
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_BYTE_STRING:
        proc set_mutability with node, RUST_LIT_STRING
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_CHAR:
        proc set_mutability with node, RUST_LIT_CHAR
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_TRUE:
        proc set_mutability with node, RUST_LIT_BOOL
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_FALSE:
        proc set_mutability with node, RUST_LIT_BOOL
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parenthesised expression, unit `()`, or tuple `(a, b)`. A single element with no
trailing comma is just a parenthesised expression; otherwise a tuple. `()` is the
unit value.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume '('. If ')' return RUST_UNIT. Parse expressions separated by ','. If one
element and no trailing comma return RUST_PAREN wrapping it; else RUST_TUPLE_EXPR.
Consume ')'.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_paren_or_tuple" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return proc make_node with RUST_UNIT
    End If

    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_TUPLE_EXPR
    Let count be 0
    Let trailing be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let pt be proc peek with parser
        If pt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN:
            Break
        End If
        If pt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If
        Let elem be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with node, elem
        Set count to count plus 1
        Set trailing to 0
        Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        If comma is equal to 1:
            Set trailing to 1
            Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')'"

    If count is equal to 1:
        If trailing is equal to 0:
            Let inner be proc node_child with node, 0
            Let pn be proc make_node with RUST_PAREN
            proc add_child with pn, inner
            Return pn
        End If
    End If
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Array literal `[a, b, c]` or repeat `[x; N]`. The repeat form stores the element
and count; the list form stores all elements.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume '['. If immediately ']' return an empty RUST_ARRAY_EXPR. Parse the first
expression; if ';' follows parse the count and mark a repeat (mutability=1) with
two children; otherwise gather comma-separated elements. Consume ']'.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_array_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_ARRAY_EXPR

    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return node
    End If

    Let first be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with node, first

    Let semi be proc peek with parser
    If semi is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let count be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with node, count
        proc set_mutability with node, 1
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET, "Expected ']'"
        Return node
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        If comma is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Let nt be proc peek with parser
        If nt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET:
            Break
        End If
        Let elem be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with node, elem
    End While

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET, "Expected ']'"
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Closure `|args| body` or `move |args| body`, and the zero-arg `|| body`. The body
is a single expression (which may itself be a block). Parameters are simple
patterns with optional type annotations.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume optional 'move'. If '||' the param list is empty (consume it); else consume
'|', parse params (pattern + optional ': type') until '|'. Then parse the body
expression. Children: the param patterns followed by the body (last child).
Returns RUST_CLOSURE.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_closure" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_CLOSURE

    Let mv be proc peek with parser
    If mv is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_MOVE:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc set_mutability with node, 1
    End If

    Let pp be proc peek with parser
    If pp is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PIPEPIPE:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_PIPE, "Expected '|'"
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let t be proc peek with parser
            If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_PIPE:
                Break
            End If
            If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Break
            End If
            Let pat be proc parse_pattern with parser
            Let param be proc make_node with RUST_PARAM
            proc add_child with param, pat
            Let ct be proc peek with parser
            If ct is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_COLON:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let ty be proc parse_type with parser
                proc set_type_info with param, ty
            End If
            proc add_child with node, param
            Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
            If comma is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
        End While
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_PIPE, "Expected '|'"
    End If

    Let body be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with node, body
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Path-led expression: an identifier or qualified path that may continue into a
macro call `name!(...)`/`name!{...}`/`name![...]`, a struct literal `Path { f: v,
.. }`, or a plain path/identifier. Struct literals are only recognised when a '{'
follows a bare path (the caller's context ensures we are in an expression position
where a struct literal is valid).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Build the path name across '::' segments (and consume turbofish `::<...>` generic
args). Then: '!' -> macro call (consume the delimited token group); '{' -> struct
literal with field inits; else a RUST_IDENTIFIER/RUST_PATH node named by the path.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_path_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let name be proc current_lexeme with parser
    proc advance_token with parser

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let s be proc peek with parser
        If s is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_SCOPE:
            Break
        End If
        proc advance_token with parser
        Note: turbofish ::<...>
        Let tf be proc peek with parser
        If tf is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
            proc skip_angle_group with parser
            Otherwise:
            Let seg be proc current_lexeme with parser
            Let combined be proc str_append with name, "::"
            Set combined to proc str_append with combined, seg
            Set name to combined
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If
    End While

    Let t be proc peek with parser

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_BANG:
        Return proc parse_macro_call with parser, name
    End If

    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
        Note: struct literal Path { ... } only if it looks like field inits
        Let ok be proc looks_like_struct_literal with parser
        If ok is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_struct_literal with parser, name
        End If
    End If

    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_IDENTIFIER
    proc set_name with node, name
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Heuristic guard for struct-literal recognition. A bare `Path {` in expression
position is a struct literal, but `if cond { }` style contexts already routed
through their own parsers, so by the time we are here a following '{' after a path
is a struct literal. This always returns 1; the dedicated control-flow parsers
consume their own braces before reaching here.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns 1. The grammar position guarantees a struct literal here.
@End Implementation
Process called "looks_like_struct_literal" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a struct literal `Path { field: value, ..base }`. Each field init is a
RUST_STRUCT_FIELD_INIT carrying the field name and a value child; shorthand `field`
(no `: value`) is supported; the functional-update `..base` is consumed as a final
spread child.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume '{'. Loop until '}'/EOF: on '..' parse the base expression as a spread
child; otherwise read the field name, and if ':' parse the value, else use the
field name as an identifier value (shorthand). Build RUST_STRUCT_FIELD_INIT and
attach. Trailing comma permitted. Consume '}'. Returns RUST_STRUCT_EXPR named by
the path.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_struct_literal" takes parser as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_STRUCT_EXPR
    proc set_name with node, name

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE:
            Break
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If

        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_DOTDOT:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let base be proc parse_expression with parser
            proc add_child with node, base
            Otherwise:
            Let fname be proc current_lexeme with parser
            Let init be proc make_node with RUST_STRUCT_FIELD_INIT
            proc set_name with init, fname
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let ct be proc peek with parser
            If ct is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_COLON:
                proc advance_token with parser
                Let val be proc parse_expression with parser
                proc add_child with init, val
                Otherwise:
                Note: shorthand: field name is also the value identifier
                Let idn be proc make_node with RUST_IDENTIFIER
                proc set_name with idn, fname
                proc add_child with init, idn
            End If
            proc add_child with node, init
        End If

        Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
        If comma is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE, "Expected '}'"
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses a macro call `name!(...)`, `name![...]`, or `name!{...}`. The token group
inside the matching delimiter is consumed (its contents are kept as raw arguments
only structurally - the call node records the macro name and a flat list of the
top-level comma-separated argument expressions when the delimiter is parentheses,
which covers println!/vec!/format! style usage).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume '!'. On '(' parse comma-separated expression arguments until ')'. On '['
parse comma-separated expression arguments until ']'. On '{' consume the balanced
brace group (treated opaque). Returns RUST_MACRO_CALL named by the macro path.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_macro_call" takes parser as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_MACRO_CALL
    proc set_name with node, name

    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LPAREN:
        proc advance_token with parser
        proc parse_call_args with parser, node
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RPAREN, "Expected ')'"
        Return node
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        proc advance_token with parser
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let pt be proc peek with parser
            If pt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET:
                Break
            End If
            If pt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Break
            End If
            Let arg be proc parse_expression with parser
            proc add_child with node, arg
            Let comma be proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
            If comma is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
        End While
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACKET, "Expected ']'"
        Return node
    End If
    If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let depth be 1
        While depth is greater than 0:
            Let c be proc peek with parser
            If c is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Break
            End If
            If c is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE:
                Set depth to depth plus 1
            End If
            If c is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE:
                Set depth to depth minus 1
            End If
            proc advance_token with parser
        End While
        Return node
    End If

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Skips a balanced `<...>` group (a turbofish or generic-arg list) tracking nesting
so an inner `<` does not end it early. Used when a path uses `::<...>`.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume '<'; depth=1; advance until depth returns to 0 on the matching '>'.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_angle_group" takes parser as Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let depth be 1
    While depth is greater than 0:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LT:
            Set depth to depth plus 1
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_GT:
            Set depth to depth minus 1
        End If
        proc advance_token with parser
    End While
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Control-flow Expressions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
if / if-let / else-if / else. The condition is parsed in no-struct-literal context
implicitly because struct literals require an explicit path-{ which the condition
grammar still admits; for translation fidelity we parse a full expression. if-let
binds a pattern against a scrutinee.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'if'. If 'let' follows: consume, parse_pattern, '=', parse the scrutinee,
then the then-block; produce RUST_IF_LET_EXPR with pattern, scrutinee, then-block,
optional else. Otherwise parse the condition, then-block; produce RUST_IF_EXPR
with condition, then-block, optional else. The else branch may be a block or a
nested if (else-if).
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_if_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let lt be proc peek with parser
    If lt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LET:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let node be proc make_node with RUST_IF_LET_EXPR
        Let pat be proc parse_pattern with parser
        proc add_child with node, pat
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_EQ, "Expected '='"
        Let scrut be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with node, scrut
        Let then_blk be proc parse_block with parser
        proc add_child with node, then_blk
        proc parse_else_branch with parser, node
        Return node
    End If

    Let cnode be proc make_node with RUST_IF_EXPR
    Let cond be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with cnode, cond
    Let then2 be proc parse_block with parser
    proc add_child with cnode, then2
    proc parse_else_branch with parser, cnode
    Return cnode
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses an optional `else` branch and attaches it as a child of the if node. The
branch is either `else { block }` or `else if ...` (a nested if expression).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
If peek == 'else': consume; if the next is 'if' attach parse_if_expr; else attach
parse_block.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_else_branch" takes parser as Integer, node as Integer:
    Let t be proc peek with parser
    If t is not equal to Lexer.TOKEN_ELSE:
        Return
    End If
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let n be proc peek with parser
    If n is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_IF:
        Let elif be proc parse_if_expr with parser
        proc add_child with node, elif
        Otherwise:
        Let blk be proc parse_block with parser
        proc add_child with node, blk
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
match expression `match scrut { pat => body, ... }`. Each arm has a pattern, an
optional guard `if cond`, and a body expression. Arms are RUST_MATCH_ARM children;
the scrutinee is child 0.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'match'; parse the scrutinee; '{'. Loop until '}': parse a pattern; if 'if'
follows parse a guard (stored as the arm's value-held expression via a child);
'=>'; parse the arm body expression; build RUST_MATCH_ARM (pattern, [guard], body)
and attach. Optional ',' between arms. Consume '}'. Returns RUST_MATCH_EXPR.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_match_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_MATCH_EXPR

    Let scrut be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with node, scrut

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_LBRACE, "Expected '{'"

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let t be proc peek with parser
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE:
            Break
        End If
        If t is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_EOF:
            Break
        End If

        Let arm be proc make_node with RUST_MATCH_ARM
        Let pat be proc parse_pattern with parser
        proc add_child with arm, pat

        Let gt be proc peek with parser
        If gt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_IF:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let guard be proc parse_expression with parser
            proc set_value with arm, guard
        End If

        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_FATARROW, "Expected '=>'"
        Let body be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with arm, body
        proc add_child with node, arm

        proc accept with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_COMMA
    End While

    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_RBRACE, "Expected '}'"
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
loop expression `loop { block }`. The body is the single child.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'loop'; parse the body block as child. Returns RUST_LOOP_EXPR.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_loop_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_LOOP_EXPR
    Let body be proc parse_block with parser
    proc add_child with node, body
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
while and while-let. `while cond { body }` and `while let pat = scrut { body }`.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'while'. If 'let' follows: consume, pattern, '=', scrutinee, body block ->
RUST_WHILE_LET_EXPR (pattern, scrutinee, body). Otherwise condition + body block ->
RUST_WHILE_EXPR (condition, body).
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_while_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser

    Let lt be proc peek with parser
    If lt is equal to Lexer.TOKEN_LET:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let node be proc make_node with RUST_WHILE_LET_EXPR
        Let pat be proc parse_pattern with parser
        proc add_child with node, pat
        proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_EQ, "Expected '='"
        Let scrut be proc parse_expression with parser
        proc add_child with node, scrut
        Let body be proc parse_block with parser
        proc add_child with node, body
        Return node
    End If

    Let wnode be proc make_node with RUST_WHILE_EXPR
    Let cond be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with wnode, cond
    Let body2 be proc parse_block with parser
    proc add_child with wnode, body2
    Return wnode
End Process

@Reasoning:
for-each `for pat in iter { body }`. The iteration pattern, the iterable
expression, and the body block are the three children.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Consume 'for'; parse the pattern; 'in'; parse the iterable expression; parse the
body block. Returns RUST_FOR_EXPR (pattern, iterable, body).
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_for_expr" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    proc advance_token with parser
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_FOR_EXPR

    Let pat be proc parse_pattern with parser
    proc add_child with node, pat
    proc expect with parser, Lexer.TOKEN_IN, "Expected 'in'"
    Let iter be proc parse_expression with parser
    proc add_child with node, iter
    Let body be proc parse_block with parser
    proc add_child with node, body
    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructs a RUST_BINARY_OP node from an operator lexeme and two operand children.
Centralised so every binary-precedence level builds the node identically.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make RUST_BINARY_OP; set value=op; add lhs then rhs; return.
@End Implementation
Process called "make_binary" takes op as Integer, lhs as Integer, rhs as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node be proc make_node with RUST_BINARY_OP
    proc set_value with node, op
    proc add_child with node, lhs
    proc add_child with node, rhs
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Concatenates two NUL-terminated byte strings into a freshly allocated owned
buffer. Used to assemble qualified path names ("a" + "::" + "b") and use-tree
text. A null operand is treated as an empty string so callers need not guard.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Compute both lengths by scanning to NUL. Allocate len_a+len_b+1. Copy a then b,
write the trailing NUL, return the buffer.
@End Implementation
Process called "str_append" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let la be 0
    If a is not equal to 0:
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let ca be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with a, la
            If ca is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
            Set la to la plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Let lb be 0
    If b is not equal to 0:
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let cb be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with b, lb
            If cb is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
            Set lb to lb plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Let total be la plus lb
    Let buf be proc allocate from Layout with total plus 1
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than la:
        Let x be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with a, i
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buf, i, x
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than lb:
        Let y be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with b, j
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buf, la plus j, y
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buf, total, 0
    Return buf
End Process
